  <p data-reveal>There are questions the mind can't answer on its own. Why do I shut down whenever someone gets too close? Why is it hard to breathe deeply when there's conflict? Why, despite perfectly understanding what's going on with me, do I keep repeating the same patterns? The answer, often, isn't only in thought — it's in the body. And that's precisely what Core Energetics came to say.</p>

  <h2 data-reveal>From Reich to Pierrakos: the body as an emotional archive</h2>
  <p data-reveal>Core Energetics has a clear lineage. Wilhelm Reich, a psychoanalyst and student of Freud, was the first to propose that psychological defenses aren't only mental: they install themselves in muscle tissue, in restricted breathing, in posture. He called it "character armor" — an armor the body builds to protect us from what was too much to feel.</p>
  <p data-reveal>Alexander Lowen took up that legacy and developed Bioenergetics, a form of therapeutic work that integrated movement, voice, and grounding — the body's connection with the earth — as central tools of the process. But it was John Pierrakos, co-founder alongside Lowen and a foundational figure in this lineage, who took the next step: integrating that vision of the energetic body with a spiritual understanding of the person. Influenced by the teachings of the Pathwork — a path of inner development he explored with Eva Pierrakos and that Susan Thesenga helped systematize — Pierrakos understood that healing didn't mean only feeling better psychologically. It meant reconnecting with something deeper: a dimension of being that remains intact beneath all the wounds.</p>
  <p data-reveal>That's Core Energetics: a bridge between the body, the psyche, and the spiritual dimension of human experience. Barbara Brennan, whose work with the human energy field complements this tradition, describes something similar when she speaks of the aura as a living system that records our emotional history with sometimes surprising precision.</p>

  <h2 data-reveal>What the body doesn't forget</h2>
  <p data-reveal>I work with this every day in my practice. A sunken chest can speak of a sadness that was never cried — maybe because there was no space, maybe because no one was there for it. A permanently clenched jaw can be the imprint of an anger that found the door closed too many times. Shoulders that carry downward can be the physical record of having taken on, very early on, a responsibility that wasn't yours.</p>
  <p data-reveal>The body doesn't lie. And it doesn't judge either: it only remembers.</p>
  <p data-reveal>In Core Energetics work, Anna Timmermans — whose book <em>Beyond Defense</em> is a foundational reference text in this tradition — describes with precision how each bodily pattern has an emotional and relational logic. Jorge Galindo, from Mexico, has explored this same dimension in <em>Viaje al centro del cuerpo y de la mente</em>, connecting the theory to the reality of the Latin American body and its particular ways of carrying the unspoken.</p>
  <p data-reveal>My direct teacher, Lael Keen, integrates all of this with a clinical and spiritual sensibility that runs through every aspect of the work. With her I learned that approaching the body in therapy isn't a technique: it's an act of listening. The work includes movement, voice, breath, grounding, and above all presence — the willingness to accompany what emerges when energy begins to move where it was blocked.</p>
  <p data-reveal>Because that's what it's about: not forcing anything, but creating the conditions for the nervous system and the body to remember there's another possibility. That things don't have to stay this way.</p>
  <p data-reveal>This process connects naturally with other approaches I use in practice. <a href="/en/blog/somatic-experiencing/" class="link-underline">Somatic Experiencing</a> works with incomplete activation cycles that also live in the tissue. <a href="/en/blog/polyvagal-theory/" class="link-underline">Polyvagal Theory</a> offers a precise map of how the nervous system regulates — or loses regulation — in response to the environment. And <a href="/en/blog/body-based-therapy/" class="link-underline">body-based therapy</a> as a broader field shares with Core Energetics the conviction that the body is always a valid entry point, sometimes the most honest one.</p>

  <h2 data-reveal>The deeper question</h2>
  <p data-reveal>Some people come to therapy seeking relief — and that's completely legitimate. But others arrive with a different, broader question: who am I beyond my wounds? What's left when I stop carrying what was never mine?</p>
  <p data-reveal>Pierrakos understood that therapeutic work, at its deepest level, could lead us to contact a broader dimension of existence. Not from outside, not from doctrine, but from within — from the body itself beginning to loosen and breathe. In the Pathwork tradition this is named as the Higher Self: that part of us that was never damaged, that was always there.</p>
  <p data-reveal>I don't impose this language in session. But when someone is ready to ask, Core Energetics has the tools and the horizon to accompany that path.</p>
  <p data-reveal>What I've found, again and again, is this: every chronic tension is also a form of self-love misdirected. The body did the best it could with what it had. The armor you built protected you. The work isn't to destroy it — it's to gently ask whether it's still necessary.</p>
  <p data-reveal>Healing, from this perspective, isn't fixing something broken. It's recovering the vitality that was interrupted. It's coming back to inhabit yourself.</p>
  <p data-reveal>If you're interested in exploring how this work could be part of your process, you can review <a href="/en/blog/what-to-expect/" class="link-underline">what to expect from therapy</a> or write to me directly for a first conversation.</p>
